SIMPLE: spinet
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spinet
<hw>Spin"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>espinete</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧pinette</ets> (cf. It.
<ets>spinetta</ets>), fr. L. <ets>spina</ets> a thorn; -- so called
because its quills resemble thorns. See <er>Spine</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A keyed instrument of music resembling a
harpsichord, but smaller, with one string of brass or steel wire to each
note, sounded by means of leather or quill plectrums or jacks. It was
formerly much used.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dumb spinet</b></col>. <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Manichordon</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spinet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spinet
<hw>Spi"net</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>spinetum</ets>. See <er>Spinny</er>.]</ety> <def>A spinny.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spinetail</ent>⟦br⟧
